condition: symmetry_score < 0.65 AND fill_pct > 60
insight: Low bilateral symmetry with high fill suggests a side-facing figure — NOT a front-facing symmetric character. Look at the mass distribution to determine facing direction.

condition: circular element (circ > 0.8) at front/bottom of figure, small relative to body
insight: A small circular element positioned at the front or bottom of a side-facing figure is likely a held object (acorn, ball, tool) or a paw/foot pad — not an eye (eyes are usually inside the head region).

condition: large non-convex shape above main body, fan-shaped
insight: A large flowing shape above the main body mass is likely a tail (squirrel, fox, peacock), hair, or decorative plume — NOT ears. Ears are typically smaller, pointed, and come in symmetric pairs.

condition: 67+ elements, all organic, deep nesting, side-profile
insight: Complex illustrations with 40+ organic elements and deep nesting (3+ levels) are typically detailed animal or character illustrations with layered body parts, shading regions, and decorative details — not geometric icons or logos.

condition: positive space grid shows curved silhouette, not rectangular
insight: Read the positive space grid as a low-resolution picture of the silhouette. A curved, non-rectangular outline strongly suggests an organic subject (animal, person, plant) rather than a geometric design (UI element, diagram, chart).

condition: multiple concentric groups of 2-3 elements each
insight: Concentric groups (elements sharing a center) represent detailed features like eyes (iris+pupil+highlight), wheels (rim+tire+hub), or buttons. Their position relative to the body helps identify them — on the head = eyes, on the body = buttons/details.

condition: symmetry pairs but moderate score (0.4-0.7)
insight: Moderate symmetry with defined mirror pairs means the design has symmetric FEATURES (like two eyes, two ears, paired limbs) but the overall composition is NOT symmetric — likely because it's viewed from an angle or in a dynamic pose.

condition: many elements with 0px nearest-neighbor distance
insight: Elements with 0px distance are touching or overlapping — they form a continuous visual surface. This is common in illustrations that use stacked shapes for shading, gradient simulation, or color regions rather than discrete separate parts.

condition: 4+ spatial clusters, one dominant (40+ elements)
insight: When one cluster dominates (contains most elements) and smaller clusters exist at the edges, the dominant cluster is the main body and the smaller clusters are appendages, accessories, or background elements. Analyze each cluster separately.

condition: high overlap count (IoU > 0.3 in 10+ pairs)
insight: Dense overlapping means shapes are layered on top of each other — like paint strokes building up an image. The stacking tree reveals the layering order. Don't try to interpret each shape independently — they work together to create regions.

condition: Vision: When circ=1.00, conv=1.00, and aspect=1.00 with a single closed_loop path (from A simple black circle with a thick stroke on a white backgro)
insight: The shape is a perfect circle; combined with low fill % (8%), this indicates a stroke-based outline rather than a solid fill

condition: Vision: When a single MEDIUM-sized element occupies the full canvas with centroid at (12.0, 12.0) in a 24×24 canvas (from A simple black circle with a thick stroke on a white backgro)
insight: The shape is perfectly centered and takes up most of the available space, indicating a well-composed, scalable icon design

condition: Vision: When the positive-space grid shows a symmetrical ring pattern with 12 'corners' detected (from A simple black circle with a thick stroke on a white backgro)
insight: The circle's discrete sampling creates octagonal-like artifacts in the grid, but the high circularity score confirms true roundness in the vector

condition: Vision: high corner count (385) + low circularity (0.03) + very large area + closed loop (from Solid black silhouette of a cartoon duck/waterfowl character)
insight: likely a dense silhouette outline or character boundary, not abstract organic shape

condition: Vision: aspect ratio ~1.66-1.87 + organic closed loops clustered in upper-left quadrant (bbox 50-200 x 5-140) (from Solid black silhouette of a cartoon duck/waterfowl character)
insight: head/facial region of a side-facing character

condition: Vision: semicircle_or_arc at bottom-right (E40: 214.7–251.5, 200.4–231.9) + high circularity (0.86) (from Solid black silhouette of a cartoon duck/waterfowl character)
insight: rounded extremity or gesture element (e.g., thumbs-up digit) in character pose

condition: Vision: multiple small closed loops (area 800–2100) arranged vertically on left side (x: 2–100) (from Solid black silhouette of a cartoon duck/waterfowl character)
insight: wing, flipper, or limb segmentation in side-profile character

condition: Vision: circ=1.00 AND aspect=1.00 AND centroid at canvas center (from A centered, perfectly symmetrical black circle rendered with)
insight: Perfect circular geometry with high symmetry — likely an icon, badge, or decorative element

condition: Vision: closed_loop topology with single path element (from A centered, perfectly symmetrical black circle rendered with)
insight: Stroke-only circular shape; no fill — efficient, minimal design suitable for icons or outlines

condition: Vision: bbox corners=12 with distributed positive space grid pattern (from A centered, perfectly symmetrical black circle rendered with)
insight: The corner count reflects the octagonal approximation of the circle; grid shows smooth radial boundary
